lieves that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">insufficient account has been taken on how</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> changes will impact in Scotland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Replacement of Housing Benefit by Universal Credit </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Fundamental to the government’s reform is the subsuming existing working age benefits and tax credits, including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> housing benefit, into Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (UC).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">While the merits of this project could be debated, we accept that this is the clear intention of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">overnment.  From the beginning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA has sought from ministers and officials clarity about when local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ies will lose their current role in administering housing benefit and what, if any, role may be envisaged for local authorities in the supporting the delivering of Universal Credit. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Local authorities originally understood that they would no longer be ta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">king claims for Housing Benefit (HB) after October 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, then</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> it would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">up to April 2014.  Now, local authorities have no date </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">where they can plan with certainty on the basis of this function ending.  COSLA recognises that the Department for Work and Pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nsions (DWP) have undertaken a major internal review which is resulting in a more measured approach to the implementation of UC.  Indeed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> we have earlier expressed concern regarding the timeframe and scope of the reforms.  While we therefore welcome a slow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ing down in implementation of a very complex change if the planning and infrastructure is not yet ready, this has also produced considerable difficulties for local authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.59pt; padding-left:3.41pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> are expected to keep in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a skilled </span><span style="font-fami