pt">ing benefit payments only to see rent arrears rise sharply and tenants experiencing distress. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">At the end of the quarter to June, 4 out of 6 councils sampled were projecting substantial </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">end of year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">increases in rent arrears over the 2012/2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">figure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> (One council did not provide a response and another could not provide an accurate figure)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">. These showed substantial increases in gross rent arrears at financial year end from the position at the end of the June quarter. These projected gross rent arrear i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ncreases, from 2012/13, for all 4 councils total £3.9m at year end, with projections varying from gross increases of £237k to £1.9m.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA is projecting an additional £15m in rent arrears to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Scottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">councils from under occupancy (bedroom tax) at year end.  The RSL sector has nearly as much housing stock and anecdotal feedback suggests that additional arrears in that sector are also likely to be substantial. Feedback to COSLA suggests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">£6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to £10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">m </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">councils </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">already invested in additional local supports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Councils have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">already added around £3m to the DWP allocation and we expect this figure to double. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> measure will do little to assist housing supply in Scotland.  Scotland has about 61% dwell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ings owner occupied with around 35% rented (June 2011, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Scot. Gov. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Figures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">). The rented sector is split with roughly one third each for councils, RSLs and private, thus social renting comprises around two thirds all rented properties, a much larger sector t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">han England. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In Scotland, 82,500 households are affected by under occupancy penalties, 68</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">500 (1 bed reduction) and 14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">000 (2 bed reduction). Most of those affected are likely to require one or two bedroom properties.  Scottish Government analysis estima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tes 21,657 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> bedroom properties and 27,791 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> bedroom properties available for rent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in the social sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in 2009/10 and it is likely that the current stock availability reflects this. Demand for these properties comes from housing lists and homeless app</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">licants in addition to increased demand generated by under occupancy changes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ll </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">five </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">councils, who responded in July to our sample, reflected this picture of very limited </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">stock </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">availab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">lity of 1 and 2 bedroom properties in their areas.  In total these c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ouncils estimated availability of 4697 (1 bedroom) and 5337 (2 bedroom) properties. For these local authorities, 18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">123 tenants are subject to a 1 bedroom reduction and 4229 to a 2 bedroom reduction. To put these figures in context</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> North Lanarkshire ident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ified 12,393 applicants on its Common Housing Register requiring a 1 or 2 bedroom property at April 2013, with a total annual availability of 2811 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> bedroom properties in the social sector. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Most of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">se </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">councils lacked detailed knowledge of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e numbers of 1 and 2 bedroom private rented properties in their areas. Typically, rents are more expensive in the private sector and there is likely to be no saving and likely increased housing benefit expenditure if tenants move into that sector to avoid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a reduction.  Additionally, the composition of the private sector is very variable with most smaller sized properties only available on a sharing basis, with prospective tenants having already identified a flat sharer. In many areas outside cities, the pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">vate sector market is limited, e.g. North Ayrshire, or affected by holiday lets, e.g. Highland. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Possible moves to available properties are also constrained by issues of employment, travel, family responsibilities and community ties.  In some rural areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">like Highland (the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">size of Belgium) remoteness and sparse populat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is especially relevant, where 24 communities have no 1 bedroom accommodation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Therefore, for the majority of tenants affected by under occupancy penalties in Scotland, there are likely t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o be very limited opportunities to avoid the penalty through moving to a suitability sized property in the near future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">This is a policy which is ill conceived and not working. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Discretionary Housing Payments are really only suitable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> support short term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> yet the availability of 1 and 2 bedroom properties means that many households will be stuck in this situation longer term.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Fourteen per cent and 25% reductions are much greater than typical rent differentials for differing sizes of properties in most a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">reas of Scotland.  Any reductions being applied should reflect actual rent differentials in social housing in an area. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">The Government also needs to adopt a clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for people with disabilities and care needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> separated parents who have access to children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> rather than leaving this to discretionary help through DHPs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Direct Payments </span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Paying all benefits as a direct monthly payment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> under Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">represents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> a major step</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">which needs phased in very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">gradually and carefully. We agree with the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">cottish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ederation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ssociations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and the NFHA that the best way to protect residents is for the Government to allow them to choose to have the rent support payment made direct to their landlords. Otherw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ise tenants risk getting into unmanageable arrears.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA believes that the Government has seriously under estimated the impact that this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">will have on social landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> income streams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> and the major re organisation and new investments councils and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">SLs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> have to undertake to mitigate impacts.  COSLA has estimated the potential for increased rent arrears of £50m for councils in Scotland and potentially similar impacts on RSLs. While there has been important learning from the Direct Payment Demonstration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> Projects, any success they have had in rent collection, has only come about from an unprece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ed commitment of staff resources which will be unsustainable when the full impact of UC direct payments hits councils and RSLs. Besides, the DPDPs are limited t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">o housing benefit and behaviours may be quite different when all benefits are wrapped up in a single monthly UC payment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA welcomes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">recent announcements by Lord Freud on the proposals to switchback to landlord payments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">f arrears reach two month’s re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">nt, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in part responsive to the concerns we and others have expressed. While we think these measures will help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to mitigate arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">, they will not remove the risk to councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> rental streams which are already being impacted from under occupancy.  Much will de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">pend on how efficient will be DWP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s implementation of these proposals and we have as yet no detail of how this will operate in practice.  Councils and RSLs will also need to make their own staff and system investments to support these arrangements and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">thos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for alternate payment arrangements. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">It is important that the full cost of these additional investments is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">included</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> in the resources which DWP propose to make available under the proposed Local Support Services Framework to support UC.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">While the Governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ent has moved to increase the safeguards necessary to support its plans, the risks represented by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">direct payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> could well outweigh any gains as many tenants embark on a difficult journey towards financial capability. DWP may well require more assistance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> than it has indicated to date</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> from councils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> to ensure the successful rollout </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">of direct payments. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">here is a real danger than should the government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">come to this conclusion, councils will no longer have in place the skilled and experienced workf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">orce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">necessary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">to assist.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In general, COSLA view both direct payments and under occupancy changes as bringing significant risks to housing investment both in exiting stock and new homes.  Housing is a devolved responsibility in Scotland and the policy env</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ironment is different to England.  To avoid de stabilisation and to secure best value for the public purse, it is therefore important that policy changes on reserved matters such as benefit support to housing costs interact effectively with devolved respon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">sibilities.  We are concerned that insufficient account has been taken of the impacts of these changes in Scotland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Homelessness Prevention</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">In Scotland, in response to our own legislation on homelessness some very significant progress has been made in addressing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">homelessness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and moving people into settled accommodation.  We believe that providing stability and support to homeless families and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">individuals is essential to reducing dependency and promoting work.  A vital element of local government’s homelessness services is the provision of temporary accommodation. Council owned temporary accommodation constitutes the majority of such accommodati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">on in Scotland.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tenants in this accommodation are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">impacted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> by Under Occupancy measures and the benefit cap, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">for both of which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> licenced or leased temporary accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> has been exempted.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Much of this accommodation has been provided in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">furnished flats in Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">These have been adapted and enhanced to meet needs (e.g. basic furniture, white goods, household utensils and security/controls to manage behavioural difficulties, throughput to more permanent accommodation etc.). There is high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">turnover in this accommodation and this along with the level of need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> of those accommodated mean that the charges, in consequence, are higher than mainstream council rents.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Since families and individuals often have little choice in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">ature of temporar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">y accommodation which is available to them, COSLA would argue that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> forms of temporary accommodation should be exempt from Under occupancy penalties and the Benefit Cap.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">also believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> that that DWP’s proposals for how temporary accommodation is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> treated under UC should reflect realistic costs of the provision of such accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> which current proposals do not do.  There is a real danger that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">changes to how housing costs of providing temporary accommodation are treated by the benefit sys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">tem will lead to a reduction in quantity and quality of such accommodation in Scotland and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">mine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> efforts to tackle homelessness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Supported Accommodation</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Another matter of concern is the treatment of supported accommodation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DWP initially based their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> on how this would be treated under benefit changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> on the very restrictive definition of ‘Supported Exempt Accommodation’ or SEA – a definition was originally designed to exempt certain types of accommodation with support from rent restrictions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Crucially this definition excludes local authority owned accommodation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA are pleased that DWP is now looking at ways to broaden what they consider to be ‘supported accommodation’ for benefit purposes  However, it is important that this includes all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> forms of supported accommodation, including in local authority property, where additional charges under HB have been allowable. Currently, COSLA is aware of Women’s refuges in one local authority where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">a single </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">service uses both council and RSL property a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">s refuges. Under recent measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> those tenants in the council property are subject to the Under Occupancy measures and Benefit Cap while thos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">e in the RSL properties are not.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">DWP intend to separate the ‘support’ element from the ‘rent’ element of funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">and localise the ‘support’ funding to local authorities and devolved administrations when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">Universal Credit is introduced. DWP state that they are not intending to reduce funding by doing this. However, COSLA is concerned that they must ensure that all supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">orted accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> where HB additional charges are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">in place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> is included in the amount of funding eventually localised. Otherwise important services to vulnerable groups may be undermined.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">COSLA is concerned that changes to how housing costs are treated by the benefit system are already increasing risks and costs for councils.  While we welcome those safeguarding measures now proposed, we are still concerned about the very real risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">posed b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">y further changes to the treatment of housing costs when Universal Credit is introduced. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>